	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Mechanical Engineering student Paul Gardner has spent months updating and refurbishing the Robinson Observatory at the University of Central Florida.</p>
<p>HeÂ’s installed cameras, filters and networks. HeÂ’s placed an order to extend Internet access to the grassy field where the observatory sits in anticipation of a new, custom-built 20-inch Ritchey-Chretien telescope that should arrive by April. It will replace the 26-inch Schmidt Cassegrian reflecting telescope that was dismantled and lifted out of the dome by crane this past May.</p>
<p>&quot;IÂ’m really excited,&quot; Gardner said. &quot;Although the new telescope is smaller than the original, youÂ’ll be able to get much sharper images. YouÂ’ll be able to do some serious research here.&quot;</p>
<p>The new, cutting-edge telescope is among many recent changes for UCFÂ’s rising astronomy program. The refurbishing of the observatory and new telescope, courtesy of $150,000 from the ProvostÂ’s Office, the College of Sciences and private donations, are more signs of the programÂ’s rise.</p>
<p>UCFÂ’s Planetary and Space Science Group has grown over the past four years from having one faculty member to six, including well-respected astronomers with several NASA research grants worth millions of dollars.</p>
<p>The department, which offers a minor but is in the process of adding undergraduate and graduate programs, has also made an arrangement with NASAÂ’s Infrared Telescope Facility on the Big Island of Hawaii that allows students and professors here to log onto the Internet and control that telescope from anywhere. The island is home to eight huge telescopes controlled by private entities, NASA, France, Japan and others that are in high demand by astronomers around the world.</p>
<p>Getting time on them is rare, and access for undergraduate students is exceptional, said Humberto Campins, a provost research professor at UCF who leads the Planetary Sciences Group.</p>
<p>&quot;ItÂ’s very rare to have this kind of access,&quot; Campins said. &quot;Most places donÂ’t do remote viewing. It gives our students and faculty a wonderful opportunity for research, another tool to do our work.&quot;</p>
<p>All these changes are part of a determined effort by UCFÂ’s Planetary Sciences Group to expand its work and gain national attention. &quot;We are among the top 10 planetary research groups in the country and we want to be among the best schools,&quot; Campins said.</p>
<p>There appears to be interest among students. When Campins started at UCF in 2002, the university had capacity for only 45 students in the introductory astronomy class. This semester more than 1,700 students are enrolled in astronomy classes.</p>
<p>UCF astronomy professors have collectively worked on millions of dollars worth of NASA projects including such high profile missions as Stardust, Deep Impact, Pathfinder and the Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity.</p>
<p>This year two top astronomers from Cornell University and the University of Colorado joined the UCF faculty. The group will work to recruit more top-notched faculty to strengthen its program, Campins said.</p>
<p>And UCF has been granted next yearÂ’s Division of Planetary Sciences annual conference, another sign of the programÂ’s growth and stature. The conference, which is scheduled for Oct. 7-12, 2007, draws hundreds of scientists each year from around the world.</p>
<p>For now, the next step for the program is getting the new telescope up and running at the Robinson Observatory.</p>
<p>&quot;It will all be fully automated,&quot; said Gardner, the mechanical engineering student. &quot;YouÂ’ll be able to access the scope from a computer anywhere and open and close the dome from your laptop. And with all the weather sensors and everything, the dome will automatically close if it starts raining.&quot;</p>
<p>With the help of the Central Florida Astronomical Society, the observatory will continue to hold public viewings each first and third Wednesday of the month. A temporary 14-inch telescope and eight smaller computerized telescopes will be available until the new telescope arrives.</p>
		
	
		
			
		
	
		
			
		
	
